// p81 — List.unique / .count + reassign-side local-shadow-global
// fix (v3.22.0).
//
// Two Quirk-side List helpers:
//
//   .unique() — fresh List with duplicates removed, first-
//               occurrence-wins order. Uses `not in` (which
//               dispatches to the existing List.contains
//               runtime) for the membership test.
//   .count(v) — count of elements that `== v`.
//
// Surfaced a real Codegen bug in the process: `count`'s body
// has `n := 0` followed by `n = n + 1`. The v3.13.0 fix made
// `n :=` create a local that shadows any global `n`, but the
// REASSIGN side (`n = n + 1`) still routed through
// updateLocalVariable which checked globalVars FIRST and wrote
// through. If the user's top-level code happened to have
// `n := "alex"` (creating @n typed String*), `n = n + 1` inside
// count() stored an Int through @n — LLVM verifier abort.
//
// updateLocalVariable now prefers a local NamedValues entry
// over a global one. Same precedence resolveVariable already
// used; the asymmetry between the two was the bug.

xs := [1, 2, 1, 3, 2, 1]
print(xs.unique())       // = [1, 2, 3]
print(xs.count(1))       // = 3
print(xs.count(2))       // = 2
print(xs.count(99))      // = 0

// Strings dedup correctly.
ys := ["a", "b", "a", "c", "b"]
print(ys.unique())       // = [a, b, c]

// Empty list — both safe.
empty := List()
print(empty.unique())    // = []
print(empty.count(1))    // = 0

// Top-level `n := "alex"` PLUS calling `count` (which has its
// own internal `n` local) — would have crashed pre-v3.22.0
// because count's `n = n + 1` wrote i32 into the String global.
n := "alex"
print(n)                 // = alex
print([1, 1, 2].count(1)) // = 2
print(n)                 // = alex (global unaffected)
